    "Unknown": "But the seventh day of God's rest was still going on (clearly not a twenty-four hour day).\n17. Without sin (ch\u00f4ris hamartias). This is the outstanding difference that must never be overlooked in considering the actual humanity of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`. He did not yield to sin. But more than this is true. There was no latent sin in Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to be stirred by temptation and no habits of sin to be overcome. But he did have \"weaknesses\" (astheneiai) common to our human nature (hunger, thirst, weariness, etc.). Satan used his strongest weapons against Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, did it repeatedly, and failed. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` remained \"undefiled\" [v_Jhn_8_46] (amiantos) in a world of sin (John `[char_John_Ref]` 8:46). This is our ground of hope, the sinlessness of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` and his real sympathy.\n17. Eukairos is an old word also (eu, well, kairos, opportunity), only here in N.T. \"For well-timed help,\" \"for help in the nick of time,\" before too late.\n17. For the sudden use of the relative hoi see Rom 3:\n17. The quick and the dead ( z\u00f4ntas kai nekrous ). &quot;Living and dead.&quot; Those living at the time and those already dead (1Th 4:15).\nVerse 17 For the time is come ( hoti ho kairos ). No predicate, probably estin (is) to be supplied. The phrase that follows comes from the vision of Ezekiel (chapter Ezek 9:1ff.). The construction is unusual with tou arxasthai (genitive articular aorist middle infinitive of arch\u00f4 ), not exactly purpose or result, and almost in apposition (epexegetic), but note tou elthein used as subject in Luke 17:\n17. We ought ( h\u00eameis opheilomen ). Emphatic h\u00eameis again. For opheil\u00f4 see 1Jn 2:\nVerse 17 Whoso hath ( hos an ech\u00eai ). Indefinite relative clause with modal an with hos and the present active subjunctive of ech\u00f4 . The world's goods ( ton bion tou kosmou ). &quot;The living or livelihood (not z\u00f4\u00ea , the principle of life, and see 1Jn 2:16 for bios ) of the world&quot; (not in the sense of evil or wicked, but simply this mundane sphere). Beholdeth ( the\u00f4rei ). Present active subjunctive of the\u00f4re\u00f4 , like echei just before. In need ( chreian echonta ). &quot;Having need&quot; (present active predicate participle of ech\u00f4 , agreeing with adelphon ). See the vivid picture of a like case in Jas 2:\n17. Verse 24 And he in him ( kai autos en aut\u00f4i ). That is &quot;God abides in him&quot; as in 1Jn 4:\n17. The aetos in Mat 24:28; Luke 17:37 may be a form of vulture going after carrion, but not in Rev 8:13; Rev 12:\n17. Verse 8 Draw nigh to God ( eggisate t\u00f4i the\u00f4i ). First aorist active imperative of eggiz\u00f4 , late verb from eggus (near) as in Mat 3:\nVerse 17 To him that knoweth ( eidoti ). Dative case of second perfect participle eid\u00f4s (from oida ), and with the infinitive to know how, &quot;to one knowing how.&quot; To do good ( kalon poiein ). &quot;To do a good deed.&quot; And doeth it not ( kai m\u00ea poiounti ). Dative again of the present active participle of poie\u00f4 , &quot;and to one not doing it.&quot; Cf. &quot;not a doer&quot; (Jas 1:23) and Mat 7:\nVerse 17\nVerse 17\nVerse 17\n17. Verse 8 Draw nigh to God (eggisate t\u00f4i the\u00f4i). First aorist active imperative [v_Mat_3_2] of eggiz\u00f4, late verb from eggus (near) as in Mat 3:\nVerse 17 To him that knoweth (eidoti). Dative case of second perfect participle eid\u00f4s (from oida), and with the infinitive to know how, \"to one knowing how.\" To do good (kalon poiein). \"To do a good deed.\" And doeth it not (kai m\u00ea poiounti). Dative again of the present active participle of poie\u00f4, \"and to one not doing it.\" Cf. \"not a doer\" (Jas 1:23) and Mat 7:\n17. We ought (h\u00eameis opheilomen). Emphatic h\u00eameis again. For opheil\u00f4 see 1Jn 2:\nVerse 17 Whoso hath (hos an ech\u00eai). Indefinite relative clause with modal an with hos and the present active subjunctive of ech\u00f4. The world's goods (ton bion tou kosmou). \"The living or livelihood (not z\u00f4\u00ea, the principle of life, and see 1Jn 2:16 for bios) of the world\" (not in the sense of evil or wicked, but simply this mundane sphere). Beholdeth (the\u00f4rei). Present active subjunctive of the\u00f4re\u00f4, like echei just before. In need (chreian echonta). \"Having need\" (present active predicate participle of ech\u00f4, agreeing with adelphon). See the vivid picture of a like case in Jas 2:\n17. Verse 24 And he in him (kai autos en aut\u00f4i). That is \"God abides in him\" as in 1Jn 4:\nVerse 17 That no man should be able to buy or to sell (hina m\u00ea tis dun\u00eatai agorasai \u00ea p\u00f4l\u00easai). Final clause with hina and present middle subjunctive of dunamai with aorist active infinitives. This is a regular boycott (Ramsay, Seven Letters, p. 106f.) against all not worshippers of the emperor. Save (ei m\u00ea). \"If not,\" \"except.\" Even the name (to onoma). No \"even,\" just apposition with charagma (the mark). Or the number (\u00ea ton arithmon). The stamp (the mark) may bear either the name or the number of the beast. The name and the number are one and the same. They could write the name in numerals, for numbers were given by letters. Swete suggests that it was \"according to a sort of gematria known to the Apocalyptist and his Asian readers, but not generally intelligible.\"",
    "Arthur W. Pink": "The \u201cPharisees\u201d were their theological opponents. These two rival sects hated each other most bitterly, yet, in this evil work of persecuting the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, they buried their differences, and eagerly joined together in the common crime. The same thing is witnessed in connection with Herod and Pilate: \u201cAnd Herod with his men of war set him at nought, and mocked him, and arrayed him in a gorgeous robe, and sent him again to Pilate. And the same day Pilate and Herod were made friends together: for before they were at enmity [v_Luk_23_11] between themselves\u201d (Luke 23:11, 12)! Each of these cases was a fulfillment of the prophecy which the Holy Spirit had given through David `[char_David_Rut_4]` long before: \u201cThe kings of the earth set themselves, and the rulers take counsel together, against the Lord, and against His Christ\u201d [v_Psa_2_2] (\nverse 17?\n17. An EXPOSITION of the Gospel of JOHN by A.W. Pink Volume Three [v_Jhn_15_7] [v_Jhn_15_8] [v_Jhn_15_9] [v_Jhn_15_10] [v_Jhn_15_11] [v_Jhn_15_12] [v_Jhn_15_13] [v_Jhn_15_14] [v_Jhn_15_15] [v_Jhn_15_16] John `[char_John_Ref]` 15:7-16 \u2013 21:15-25 Grace-eBooks.com An EXPOSITION of the Gospel of JOHN by A.W. Pink Volume Three [v_Jhn_15_7] [v_Jhn_15_8] [v_Jhn_15_9] [v_Jhn_15_10] [v_Jhn_15_11] [v_Jhn_15_12] [v_Jhn_15_13] [v_Jhn_15_14] [v_Jhn_15_15] [v_Jhn_15_16] John `[char_John_Ref]` 15:7-16 \u2013 21:15-25 Grace-eBooks.com JOHN 15:7-16 CHRIST THE TRUE VINE (CONCLUDED) Below is an Analysis of the second section of John `[char_John_Ref]` 15: \u2014\nverse 17?\nverse 17?\nverse 17?\nverse 17?\nverse 17?",
