    "Unknown": "[v_Exo_16_30] A sabbath rest (sabbatismos). Late word from sabbatiz\u00f4 (Ex 16:30) to keep the Sabbath, apparently coined by the author (a doubtful passage in Plutarch). Here it is parallel with katapausis (cf. Rev 14:13). For the people of God (t\u00f4i la\u00f4i tou theou). Dative case of [v_Gal_6_16] blessed personal interest to the true Israel (Gal 6:16).\nVerse 9 Using hospitality ( philoxenoi ). &quot;Friendly to strangers,&quot; old word (from philos, xenos ), in N.T. only here and 1Ti 3:2; Tit 1:\n9. One should not forget that this language is glorious imagery, not actual objects in heaven. God is spirit. The picture of God on the throne is common in the O.T. and the N.T. (Mat 5:34; Mat 23:22; Heb 1:3 and in nearly every chapter in the Revelation, Rev 1:4, etc.). The use of kath\u00eamenos (sitting) for the name of God is like the Hebrew avoidance of the name Jahweh and is distinguished from the Son in Rev 6:16; Rev 7:\nVerse 9 When the living creatures shall give ( hotan d\u00f4sousin ta z\u00f4a ). Indefinite temporal clause with hotan and the future active indicative ( d\u00f4sousin ) rather than the more common second aorist active subjunctive ( d\u00f4sin ) with the notion of repetition rather than unbroken continuance, &quot;whenever they give.&quot; The giving of praise and glory to God by the four living creatures (representatives of nature) is met by corresponding worship by the redeemed (the four and twenty elders). &quot;Created life adores the Uncreated&quot; (Swete), &quot;to the one living for ages of ages.&quot;\n9. Cf. Jas 2:5-7; Jas 5:1-\nVerse 9\nVerse 9\nVerse 9\nVerse 9\n9. Cf. Jas 2:5-7; Jas 5:1-\nVerse 9 Doeth no sin (hamartian ou poiei). Linear present active indicative as in\nverse 1Jn 3:4 like hamartanei in\nverse 1Jn 3:\n9. One should not forget that this language is glorious imagery, not actual objects in heaven. God is spirit. The picture of God on the [v_Mat_5_34] throne is common in the O.T. and the N.T. (Mat 5:34; Mat 23:22; [v_Heb_1_3] Heb 1:3 and in nearly every chapter in the Revelation, Rev 1:4, etc.). The use of kath\u00eamenos (sitting) for the name of God is like the Hebrew avoidance of the name Jahweh and is distinguished from [v_Rev_6_16] the Son in Rev 6:16; Rev 7:\nVerse 9 When the living creatures shall give (hotan d\u00f4sousin ta z\u00f4a). Indefinite temporal clause with hotan and the future active indicative (d\u00f4sousin) rather than the more common second aorist active subjunctive (d\u00f4sin) with the notion of repetition rather than unbroken continuance, \"whenever they give.\" The giving of praise and glory to God by the four living creatures (representatives of nature) is met by corresponding worship by the redeemed (the four and twenty elders). \"Created life adores the Uncreated\" (Swete), \"to the one living for ages of ages.\"\n9. Note the accusative after proskune\u00f4 as in verse Rev 13:8. [v_Rev_13_3] Here the death-stroke of one of the heads (verse Rev 13:3) is ascribed to the beast. Clearly the delegated authority of the provincial priests of the emperor-worship is rigorously enforced, if this is the correct interpretation.\n9. See Eph 1:17 for \"a spirit of wisdom and of understanding.\" He that understands (ho ech\u00f4n noun). \"The one having intelligence\" in such matters. Cf. the adverb nounech\u00f4s (discreetly) [v_Mrk_12_34] in Mark 12:",
