    "Ruckman, Dr. Peter S_": "of that passage. Subtracting from what God said was the first sin ever committed on this earth (see how Eve `[char_Eve_Ref]` leaves out the word \u201cfreely\u201d from what God said in Gen. [v_Gen_3_2] 2:16\u2014see Gen. 3:2 and comments in that Commentary). Omission is the hallmark of Satanic New Age versions of the Bible (see our [v_Psa_91_11] comments on Psa. 91:11 in Vol. I of that Commentary). Now if the first temptation was Arminianism (do it yourself), this temptation is Calvinism\u2014let God do the whole thing for you. If you won\u2019t do it yourself and you won\u2019t let the Devil do it for you, then let God do the whole thing while you sit back on your dead can and do nothing. Don\u2019t receive Christ as you are commanded to [v_Jhn_1_12] do in John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:12; just wait till God elects you through irresistible grace against your will\u2014that\u2019s Calvinism. Bob Jones Sr. used to say, \u201cGod won\u2019t do anything for a man that he can do for himself.\u201d God knew you couldn\u2019t save yourself, so He made the payment for your sins for you. But there\u2019s something [v_Act_16_31] you have to do in salvation, and that\u2019s believe (Acts 16:31) and [v_Jhn_1_12] receive (John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:12). God\u2019s not going to make you or force you to do either one of those things. That\u2019s your part in salvation. One time, two guys were out on a lake in a rowboat when one of those big Summer thunderstorms came up. One guy said, \u201cUh oh, there\u2019s a storm coming; we\u2019d better pray.\u201d The `[group_Word_Luk_1]` other guy said, \u201cOK, you pray and I\u2019ll row.\u201d It takes both, see. You do your part, and God does His part\u2014AND YOU DO HAVE A PART TO DO. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` doesn\u2019t flinch a bit when Satan pulls the Scriptures on Him; He quotes an appropriate text right back at him: \u201cIt is said, [v_Deu_6_16] Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God\u201d (cf. Deut. 6:16). In other words, don\u2019t intentionally do something stupid and expect God to bail you out. A lot of young people sow their wild oats and spend the rest of their lives praying for a crop failure. The rule is: [v_Gal_6_7] \u201cWhatsoever a man soweth, that shall he also reap\u201d (Gal. 6:7). If you are stupid enough to run a red light, don\u2019t be surprised if God lets someone \u201cT-bone\u201d you. Note in\nverse 11 under 5:26. 12 And it came to pass in those days, that he went out into a mountain to pray, and continued all night in prayer to God. 13 And when it was day, he called unto him his disciples: and of them he chose twelve, whom also he named apostles; 14 Simon, (whom he also named Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`,) and Andrew his brother, James and John `[char_John_Ref]`, Philip and Bartholomew, 15 Matthew and Thomas, James the son of Alphaeus, and Simon called Zelotes, 16 And Judas the brother of James, and Judas Iscariot, which also was the traitor. We have already commented on Christ\u2019s all-night prayer meetings under 5:16 (which see). Here He consults His Father as to which disciples He should choose as His apostles. At least three times in His high priestly prayer, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` says the Father gave Him [v_Jhn_17_11] the twelve apostles (John `[char_John_Ref]` 17:11\u201312, 24). The only one of them that [v_Jhn_17_12] was lost was Judas Iscariot (John `[char_John_Ref]` 17:12), but even he was purposefully chosen by Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` under the leadership of the Father [v_Jhn_6_70] (John `[char_John_Ref]` 6:70\u201371). The word \u201capostles\u201d means \u201csent ones.\u201d They are the disciples who were \u201csent forth\u201d by Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to preach \u201cto the lost sheep of [v_Mat_10_5] the house of Israel\u201d in Matthew 10:5\u20137. [v_Luk_6_13] \u201cOf them he chose twelve\u201d: that\u2019s found in Luke 6:",
